explanation:
- OS_CHECK_POINTER: Macro invoked at function start. Its behaviour (does it return, abort, or just warn) determines reachability of the rest of the function; needed to know if the assignment can ever execute.  
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: The function that produces return_code and local_id; its contract/implementation determines when return_code == OS_SUCCESS and what local_id values can be produced (critical to determine whether the bit-set operation can be executed/has effect).  
- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_STREAM: The object-type argument passed into OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex; needed to know how that call validates objid and therefore whether OS_SUCCESS is possible.  
- OS_SUCCESS: The success return value tested by the if; required to interpret possible return_code outcomes from OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex.  
- OS_FdSet (struct): The definition of Set, especially the object_ids member type and array size, is needed to decide if the bit-set write can modify program state and whether it can be a no-op (e.g. out-of-range indices).  
- osal_index_t (typedef): Type, range and signedness of local_id affect shift/index calculation and bounds reasoning for the object_ids array.  
- osal_id_t (typedef): Type and valid value domain for objid influence analysis of whether OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex can ever return success for given objid values.  
- OS_SelectFdIsSet: Function(s) that read these same bits (or the higher-level semantics of how the fd set is used); required to determine if clearing/setting the bit affects behaviour (i.e., whether the write has any observable effect elsewhere).  
- OS_SelectFdClear: Related modifier of the same object_ids; its semantics are needed to reason about whether the add operation is redundant given other operations.  
- OS_SelectFdZero: Related initializer/clear routine; needed to reason about initial state of bits and whether the add operation can have any effect.  
- OS_GetMaxForObjectType: Used (directly or indirectly) when mapping ids to indices; its value(s) constrain local_id domain and array sizing decisions.  
- OS_INVALID_POINTER: Typical return from pointer-check macros; included to identify the possible early return code from OS_CHECK_POINTER and its effect on reachability.  
- OS_printf: May be invoked by OS_CHECK_POINTER or by OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex for diagnostics; useful to understand whether the macro/function performs observable side-effects (I/O) even if the bit-set is semantically redundant.

These symbols provide the necessary information about control flow (can the assignment be reached), the domain of indices (can the assignment index be valid), and the consumers of the stored bit (do readers observe the change). All three aspects are required to determine whether the bit-set operation is executed yet removable without changing program behaviour (i.e., whether it is dead code under MISRA).
